This game is so soothing. There's something about the spinning wheel and 
manipulating the clay that I find even more soothing than an actual pottery 
wheel (which I did like but hated the mess after). The game is entirely 
freeform - every design is different and it's all under your control. You 
have to buy brushes and colours with in-game currency - which you earn by 
selling the vases you make. What I especially love about this is the 
payment system - there's no "buy 1000 coins for $0.99" going on here. 
Owning the full version is a one time fee. There are OPTIONAL additional 
add-ons (brushes and colours) that can be bought for real money, but the 
entire pack wouldn't cost more than $7. The game is fully playable and 
enjoyable without those additional add-ons and the game never tries to push 
a sale on you. That alone, for me, is enough to give a game four stars min. 
There are also no lives, no energy, etc, nothing you have to wait to refill 
before you can play again. You could play endlessly if you wanted. I wish 
this game had two features: an option to keep the vase you just made, maybe 
stick it on a shelf, and your pottery history. There is a way to save a 
photo of a piece to your phone but I don't want to clutter my phone with 
pictures of virtual pottery. An in-game gallery would be *awesome*. 
Otherwise, this is honestly one of the best games I've played in a long 
time.

From the lovely sound effects to the little tidbits of art history, this app is my go-to for relaxing or being creative. I appreciate the fact you can progress by filling orders, but at your own pace. If you wish to explore your own ideas there is no penalty, and even a reward, for creating your own things.   Downsides are that the app is very fiddly about where you are touching and it can be mystifying as to what they are looking for in a 'match' for your order.  Being OK with erasing is a must.  Bonus, and a very strong one at that, is that the online community is super friendly, helpful and welcoming.

This is a really incredible art app and it makes me sad that Infinite Dreams refuses to see it that way.  I have been using it for many years now, I even administer several Facebook groups dedicated to the art of LCP.  If you are looking for a very zen experience, a great creative outlet that is simple to learn and has amazing creative potential that nearly everyone use, this is as good as it gets. Buy the in app brush packs to expand your creative options and be sure to check out the portal to view galleries of other artists.   The only drawbacks to this app as far as I am concerned are the quests you must complete to "earn" your brushes and materials and the lack of being able to back up your progress on those quests. (On Android at least) Over the years with resets I have had to do and when installing to a new device, I have to go through the whole boring process at least 6 times. I SINCERELY hope they FIX THIS BIG PROBLEM.

A lovely and highly unusual game that is very relaxing to play. As with all Infinite Dreams games (they also make the fantastic Jelly Defence), the presentation is top notch oozing style and well considered design. A couple of minor issues... textures on the pots seem a little flat with less dynamic lighting compared to the iPad version that look almost photo realistic. However, this might be necessary in order to get the app working on a wide range of devices. It would also be nice if it were possible to store snapshots of finished pots within an in-game gallery instead of having to email the tiny images to yourself. All in all, this comes well recommended 5*.
